y, and search or score candidate actions or short sequences against the current goal as you currently understand it.\nMaintain a compact working world model of what the current level seems to contain, what actions appear to do, what the goal seems to be, what is still uncertain, and what plan currently looks best.\nBelow you are provided with the current world model from the previous turn. The default behavior is to copy it and add or remove things based on the evidence that you gathered. BEFORE EXECUTING NEW ACTIONS YOU MUST ALWAYS GIVE THE REVISED VERSION OF THE WORLD MODEL.\nYou may call `action(actions)` more than once in one Python snippet if your search or control loop needs it, but stop immediately if a result reports `game_over`, `run_complete`, `level_completed`, or `done`.\nend of world model. \nFocus on what changed most recently in `history`, update the target environment change if needed, and separate gameplay-object changes from HUD-only changes.\nWhen ready, call `action(actions)` from inside the `python` tool with the best valid action or ordered batch selected by your code. If your code has found a reliable short sequence, prefer batching it in one call.\nYou may call `action(actions)` more than once in one Python snippet if your search or control loop needs it.\nIf you include assistant text before a tool call, keep it short and use it to update the world model. Helpful optional prefixes are `World model:`, `Goal model:`, `Action model:`, `Recent findings:`, `Open questions:`, `Plan:`, and `Cross-level notes:`.\nWhen calling `python`, emit exactly the tool-call format shown elsewhere in this prompt for this model. Use only that format; do not add markdown fences, prose wrappers, or alternate tool-call syntax. Do not quote or place tool-call markup inside explanatory text; when you decide to call the tool, emit the tool call itself.\nIf you use MOUSE, include integer row and col arguments.\nEFFICIENCY BUDGET \u2014 your score on each level is (baseline_actions / your_actions)^2, so every wasted action costs you quadratically.\nLevel 1: you have used 58 actions; a strong score needs about 30 or fewer. You are 1.9x over the target.\nIf you are not steadily making progress toward the level goal, commit to your single best hypothesis and the shortest sequence that tests it \u2014 do not exhaustively scan rows/columns or enumerate every option. Test one idea, read the result, then decide.", "kind": "tool", "inContext": true}, {"label": "THINKING", "content": "I'm at 58 actions and still haven't completed the level. I've been exploring the game mechanics extensively but haven't found the winning condition.\nCurrent state:\n- Left eye: rows 54-58, cols 24-28\n- Right eye: rows 54-58, cols 34-38\nBoth eyes are at the same row (54-58), but different columns (24-28 and 34-38). They're 6 columns apart.\nI've tried:\n1. Moving eyes to various positions (up/down/left/right)\n2. Pressing SPACE at various positions\n3. Clicking on eyes, mouth, and face with MOUSE\nNone of these have completed the level.\nLet me think about this differently. Maybe the goal is to have the eyes at the INITIAL position (rows 49-53, cols 19-23 and 39-43). Let me try to get back to that position.\nFrom current (left=54-58, cols 24-28; right=54-58, cols 34-38):\n- UP: left=49, right=49\n- LEFT: left moves left, right moves right\nCurrent cols: left=24-28, right=34-38\nInitial cols: left=19-23, right=39-43\nSo I need left to go left by 5 (24->19) and right to go right by 5 (34->39).\nPressing LEFT moves left left and right right. So 5 LEFT presses should get me to the initial column positions.\nLet me try: UP, LEFT, LEFT, LEFT, LEFT, LEFT\nThis should give: left at 49-53, cols 19-23; right at 49-53, cols 39-43. That's the initial position!\nBut I already tried SPACE at the initial position and it didn't work. Maybe I need to do something else at the initial position.\nActually, wait. Let me reconsider the problem. Maybe the goal is NOT to complete t